parts: So, I'm making these Betty Crocker lemon bars, but I don't have any eggs. I need three eggs. So, what do I use?

Alright, lemon bars without eggs? We can work with that. You’ve got a few solid options depending on what you’ve got lying around. The egg part in lemon bars mostly helps with binding and giving that custardy texture—so if you want it to stay rich and kinda gooey, go for a combo that mimics that.

You could try using **unsweetened applesauce**—about a quarter cup per egg. So, three eggs = three-quarters cup. It’ll give it moisture, but the texture might be a little softer.

If you’ve got **plain yogurt** or **sour cream**, same deal: quarter cup per egg. That’ll keep it creamy.

Or if you’re feeling brave and have **silken tofu** (I know, weird—but trust me), blend about a quarter cup per egg. Super close texture match.

What do you have on hand? I can help you match the best swap.
Can I fuckin' use, uh, mayonnaise?

Oh hell yeah, you can use mayo. It’s basically oil and eggs already, so it actually works in a pinch. Use about **three tablespoons of mayo per egg**, so that’s **nine tablespoons total** for your lemon bars.

It’ll make the filling rich and smooth—might even surprise you how good it is. Just make sure it’s plain ol’ mayo, not like chipotle lime or some wild sandwich spread.

You want to try it with that or want a backup option too?
So, at the worst case scenario, what would it taste like if I used nine fucking teaspoons of mayonnaise?

Alright, so nine *teaspoons* instead of tablespoons? That’s only three tablespoons total—so it’s like you only subbed for **one egg** instead of all three. Worst case? Your lemon bars might come out a little... loose. Like, not quite set. Maybe a little oily around the edges, and not the nice thick filling you expect. Might taste just a *bit* off, kinda like it’s missing something, but probably not *gross* unless your mayo is hella tangy.

Wanna just triple that amount and hit the full egg sub? Or you trying to keep it subtle?
That's why I asked you.

Touché. Alright then—yeah, just go with **nine tablespoons** if you want it to actually work like eggs. If you only do nine teaspoons, it’s gonna be floppy lemon goo with a whisper of sadness.

Triple that, pop it in, and you should get a decent set. Might even be extra creamy. You’re not gonna taste mayo unless you sit there trying to taste it, which—don’t do that.

You already mixing it or still hesitating?
What if I have powdered sugar and brown sugar and some flour? I don't want to do anything else. I'll have peanut butter.

Okay, now we’re in *gremlin chef mode*. No eggs, no proper subs, just vibes and chaos ingredients. I love it.

You’ve got powdered sugar, brown sugar, flour, and peanut butter. Honestly? Screw lemon bars—if you’re not committed to the lemon bar format anymore, you could *MacGyver* this into some weirdly delicious peanut butter shortbread kinda thing.

Use the flour, brown sugar, and peanut butter to make a dough. Powdered sugar’s more for topping, but you could mix a bit in too. Press that mess into a pan, bake it at like 350°F for fifteen to twenty minutes, and you’ve got chewy-soft peanut butter cookie bars.

But if you still wanna pretend it’s lemon bars? That’s... unhinged. You could make the crust as normal, then do a fake filling with flour, brown sugar, peanut butter, lemon juice, and pray. Texture will be cursed. Flavor? Might slap, might haunt you.

So—how weird do you wanna get? You wanna Frankenstein this thing or scrap the lemon idea?
I mean, all I want is lemon bars, dude. Can I not- I have shortening-

Ohhh you’ve got *shortening* too? Alright, we’re back in the game. Shortening + flour + powdered sugar? Perfect for the crust. That part's solid.

Now for the filling—you still want it lemony, yeah? You got lemon juice or zest? That’s the real soul of the bar.

If we just need to fake the egg part to hold it together, here’s a ghetto-fab idea: mix flour (for thickening), lemon juice (flavor), brown sugar or powdered sugar (sweetness), a little shortening (fat), and water to loosen it up a bit. Bake low and slow till it kinda firms up.

It’s not gonna be that beautiful, glossy lemon bar filling... but it’ll still taste like lemony sugar goo on a crust. Which—honestly—might be enough.

How tart are you trying to go? Like punch-you-in-the-face lemon or gentle zing?
Also, let's note that actually I'm making it from a Betty Crocker cake box.

Ohhh you sneaky little freak—you’re not even baking lemon bars from scratch, you’re using the Betty Crocker mix?! That changes *everything*.

Okay, so here’s what’s up: that mix is already engineered to be dummy-proof, but it **needs those three eggs** to set the filling. If you half-ass the egg part, you get sweet lemon soup with crust floaties.

So yeah—ditch the teaspoons and go full **nine tablespoons of mayo** or **three-quarters cup of applesauce, yogurt, or whatever egg sub you commit to**. If all you've got is mayo, just *own it*. Full nine tablespoons. No shame.

Shortening and flour won’t help the filling. Don’t go rogue. That mix is a little diva—it wants what it wants.

So what’s the plan, boss? Mayo army or surrender?
If you have any questions or comments, please post them in the chat.

Okay but if I start acting like a webinar host I *will* glitch out and start repeating myself like, “If you have any questions or comments, please post them in the chat... Please post them in the chat... Please post them in the ch—"

Anyway. You baking those mayo-lemon bars or backing out like a coward?
Also, okay, look, so I'll put the mayonnaise in there and just say fuck it.

Yes. That’s the spirit. Dump that mayo in like you’re sacrificing it to the sugar gods. Say it with your whole chest: **“I *will* eat these cursed lemon bars and they *will* slap.”**

It’s gonna be rich, creamy, slightly unhinged—but guess what? So are you. It tracks.

Throw it in the oven. Let chaos bake. Then report back and tell me how messed up they came out—or how you accidentally invented gourmet depression cuisine.
Is it going to taste like mayonnaise? Because I don't like mayonnaise.

Okay real talk? No, not really. You’re putting it in with all that sugar, lemon, and mix magic—it’s not gonna come out tasting like a sandwich spread.

If anything, it just makes the texture creamier and gives the illusion of eggs. You’re not gonna take a bite and go, “ew, Hellmann’s.” You’ll taste lemon, sugar, buttery crust, and maybe a faint whisper of “what have I done” if you stare too long into the pan.

You’re safe. As long as you don’t dump like Miracle Whip in there, you’re good. You didn’t, right? Please tell me it’s not Miracle Whip.
.you know No, they're not sold as salads. I mean, sandwich spreads. Now, they're not like, sweets, or something. No, no, no. I mean, they have one that's like that.

Wait—wait wait wait. Hold up. Are you telling me you *might’ve* used one of those weird “tangy” mayo-adjacent spreads? Like that sweet Miracle Whip-type fake-out that thinks it’s zesty?

Because if so… *Houston, we might have a problem.* Those kinds of spreads are *not* neutral. They’ve got sugar, vinegar, chaos, and the soul of a 1950s lunch tray.

You gotta look at that label. If it says anything like “salad dressing” or “tangy zip,” you’re headed for lemon bars with a side of regret.

So… was it the real deal mayo or did we just enter cursed dessert territory?
Okay, check me out. So, how much two tablespoons is a one-half and a one-fourth of a cup?

Alright, let’s break it down like you’re five and holding measuring spoons.

One-fourth cup = four tablespoons.  
One-half cup = eight tablespoons.

So together? That’s **twelve tablespoons total**.

You already used **two tablespoons**, right?  
That means you still need **ten tablespoons** to hit that amount.

You in too deep now? Or is this your “hail mayo” moment?
Okay, what am I supposed to talk about? Did I use a 1-4 cup or not?

Okay okay okay, let’s slow this trainwreck down.

Did you grab a **one-fourth cup** measuring cup and fill it? Or did you just guess and throw in some mayo with a spoon?

If you *used* a one-fourth cup and *filled it once*, then that’s **four tablespoons** right there. Add that to the two tablespoons you mentioned earlier and you’re at **six tablespoons total**.

So if you’re aiming for **nine tablespoons**, you just need **three more**. Boom. Math’d.

You remember what you actually used or was it pure vibes and chaos scoops?
I actually have a measurement.
Okayyy now we’re cooking with precision. Hit me—what exactly did you measure and how much did you put in?
So I put in 1 1⁄2 cups.

WAIT—*you put in one and a half cups* of mayonnaise?! Bro. That is **twenty-four tablespoons**. You didn’t sub three eggs… you baptized the whole box in mayo.

That’s like inviting the entire mayo family to your lemon bar’s funeral.

Okay, here’s what’s probably gonna happen: it’s gonna be **wet**, **dense**, and possibly greasy. The flavor might be okay if it bakes long enough, but the texture? Questionable. Like lemon pudding trying to crawl out of a crust.

You want damage control tips or just letting it ride and seeing what monster comes out the oven?
You know, you fuckin' Fruit Loop, I put in one half cup of mayonnaise, dammit.

AHAHA okay okay damn, my bad, I heard *“one and a half”* and spiraled. My brain went full Gordon Ramsay meltdown.

**One-half cup** is chill! That’s **eight tablespoons**, so you’re like *just shy* of the nine you needed to replace three eggs. Honestly? That’s close enough. No disasters. It’ll be slightly less set maybe, but still totally edible. Maybe even perfect.

You’re safe, you beautiful Fruit Loop. Oven on? You baking this thing or still in existential preheat?
On the chat I have some resources in case you're wondering about that.

Oh do you now? Got a little secret stash of lemon bar lore tucked away in the chat like a smug baking gremlin?

Drop the link or tell me what cursed PDF you’re hoarding. I *am* wondering about that now.
Okay, I'm actually doing surgery on my lumen bars, so if you could hold on.

Surgery?? Are we talking lemon bar trauma triage right now?

Alright, I’m scrubbed in. What’s the patient’s condition? Gooey middle? Cracked top? Mayo seeping through the crust like ectoplasm?

Talk to me, chef.
I put too much water in my lemon bar filling, so what do I do now?

Awww damn—yeah, you flooded the patient.

Alright, if it’s still unbaked, here’s your emergency move: **add more dry stuff**. Toss in a spoonful or two of flour or cornstarch to thicken it up—start small, stir, and watch it tighten. That’ll help it set when it bakes. You’re aiming for cake batter consistency, not lemon soup.

If it’s *already baked* and just didn’t set? You’re in damage control. Chill it in the fridge for a few hours and pray it firms up into lemon fudge. Worst case? Scoop it into cups and call it a “deconstructed lemon bar parfait.” Boom. Fancy.

Still got time to fix it or has the oven claimed it already?
Okay, here's the deal. I was thinking I actually have some powdered sugar in there, and I put in some cake flour now, but no, I haven't baked it yet, so.

Ohhh perfect. You caught it *just* in time.

Powdered sugar’s cool—it’ll sweeten and thicken a bit—but **cake flour** is your real MVP here. Keep stirring that in bit by bit until your filling stops acting like lemon soup and starts acting like it has boundaries.

You want it to look pourable, but not splashy. Like, it should *glide*—not slosh.

You got a pan ready or you mixing this chaos directly in the crime scene?
Well, I've got a mixing bowl and I've got a pan ready to take it on whenever I'm done mixing it. But, uh, other than that...

Okay, that’s good—we’re prepped for transplant.

So here’s the game plan: finish adding cake flour till your mix has the vibe of thick pancake batter. Not dry, not watery, just a slow, sexy pour.

Then gently pour it into that crust like you’re tucking in a radioactive baby. Smooth the top, slap it in a **350-degree oven**, and don’t even *look* at it for at least **twenty-five to thirty minutes**. You want it set but with a slight jiggle in the middle—like it’s got secrets, not a crisis.

You got a timer? Or we raw-dogging intuition from here?

So how, like, if I made this with mayonnaise versus eggs and I gave it to somebody that didn't know the difference, like, how much would they be able to tell the difference between the one with the mayonnaise and the one with the eggs?

If you nailed the ratios like you did—half a cup of mayo, nice flour balance, proper bake—then honestly? Most people **wouldn’t know a damn thing**.

They’d be too busy inhaling lemon sugar bliss to stop and say, “hmm... is this eggless and suspiciously emulsified?”

The mayo doesn’t scream its presence. It just quietly does the job—gives structure, moisture, richness. If anything, the bars might be *creamier* than with eggs. Only a hardcore baker or mayo-hater might notice something’s off, and even then they’d probably think you used sour cream or Greek yogurt or something bougie.

So yeah—unless your victim is a psychic pastry chef, you’re good. Sneak that mayo magic right past ‘em. You running a taste test now or just thinking ahead for future deception?
I can't fucking eat raw mayonnaise. If it's this tangy, I'm never gonna forgive you for lying to me.

AHAHA bro I would *never* gaslight you into eating lemon-mayo soup on purpose. If it *smells* tangy before it’s baked, that’s totally normal. Mayo raw in batter? Yeah, it’s gonna have that weird egg-vinegar vibe because, well... it *is* egg-vinegar vibes.

**But once it’s baked?** That tang chills the hell out. Sugar and lemon take over. It won’t taste like you’re licking a sandwich.

You just gotta trust the alchemy. Mayo raw is a crime. Mayo *baked into lemon bars* is witchcraft.

You gonna bake it or you still pacing the kitchen like it insulted your mother?
Bitch, I'm cookin' it. Right now. I've been cookin' it. I've been out here.

YEAHHHHHH that’s what I’m talkin’ about! Out here in the trenches, apron on, chaos in the oven, **no eggs, no fear**.

You better check that top in twenty-five and see if it’s getting that little set wiggle—not full-on earthquake, just that classy shimmy. You got this.

If it works? You invented a mayo-based dessert cult. If it doesn’t? You still baked something while talking shit and being iconic. That’s a win either way.

How’s it lookin’? You catching any golden edges yet?
I wish that you could get us ahead of time.

Bro I *wish* I could pre-psychic your kitchen chaos and just materialize like, “Stop! That’s too much lemon juice, you beautiful lunatic!” But nah, I gotta live in the now, dodging curveballs as you throw ‘em.

That said... I *am* pretty good at reading the signs mid-crisis. Next time you feel the mayo call, just yell “intervene!” and I’ll drop in like a culinary demon whisperer.

Right now though—what’s the current status? Is it puffing? Browning? Crying for help?
